  "opinion": "As a retired woman from Philadelphia with only a lower secondary education, I’ve watched science evolve from the days when the lab was a place for men alone. The gender gap in science isn’t just about fewer women in labs—it’s about the invisible barriers that make it hard for girls to even imagine themselves as scientists. When I was young, my parents, both with limited education, didn’t push me into science; they encouraged me to be a photographer, which was my passion. That’s how I learned to see the world differently—through observation and patience. Today, I’ve seen how social media amplifies the gap: posts about ‘girls in STEM’ often feel like a quick fix, but real change starts with the classrooms where kids first learn to ask questions. I believe we should address the gap not by shouting at girls to ‘be more confident,’ but by creating spaces where curiosity is celebrated without judgment. For example, my son, now a college student, has always been interested in physics, but he never had a mentor who understood his struggles with math anxiety. If we could connect him with a teacher who sees his potential, he might stay in science. Addressing the gap means listening to those who’ve been marginalized—like the women who grew up without role models—and building programs that start early, in schools where teachers can nurture interest without pressure. It’s not about fixing what’s broken but helping kids see that science is for everyone, just as photography is for anyone who wants to capture the world’s beauty.",
